    rationaleLong: "This patient has a complete hydatidiform mole (complete molar pregnancy), a form of gestational trophoblastic disease (GTD). A complete mole occurs when an empty egg (without maternal DNA) is fertilized by one sperm that duplicates its DNA (46,XX all paternal) or by two sperm (46,XX or 46,XY), resulting in an abnormal pregnancy with no fetal tissue. The hallmark findings include: (1) 'Snowstorm' or 'cluster of grapes' pattern on ultrasound (representing swollen chorionic villi), (2) Markedly elevated beta-hCG (often > 100,000 mIU/mL, much higher than expected for gestational age), (3) Uterus larger than expected for dates, (4) No identifiable fetus or fetal heartbeat, (5) Vaginal bleeding (often brown or intermittent). Associated complications include: hyperemesis gravidarum (from very high hCG), preeclampsia before 20 weeks (extremely unusual timing - preeclampsia normally occurs after 20 weeks), hyperthyroidism (hCG has structural similarity to TSH), and theca lutein cysts (ovarian enlargement from hCG stimulation). Management: (1) Suction curettage (uterine evacuation) - the definitive treatment, (2) Rh typing and RhoGAM if Rh-negative, (3) Chest X-ray to rule out pulmonary metastases, (4) Serial beta-hCG monitoring after evacuation (weekly until undetectable, then monthly for 6-12 months) to detect persistent or malignant GTD, (5) Reliable contraception for 6-12 months during monitoring (pregnancy would interfere with hCG monitoring). A complete mole has approximately a 15-20% risk of developing into persistent/malignant GTD (invasive mole or choriocarcinoma). The emergency nurse should prepare for uterine evacuation, establish large-bore IV access, type and crossmatch blood, and provide emotional support.",
    learningObjective: "Recognize complete hydatidiform mole by snowstorm ultrasound pattern and markedly elevated beta-hCG",
