    clinicalPearls: ["Snowstorm ultrasound + very high hCG + no fetus = complete hydatidiform mole", "Complete mole: 46,XX all paternal DNA; partial mole: 69,XXY (triploid) with fetal parts", "15-20% risk of developing persistent/malignant GTD after complete mole", "Serial hCG monitoring for 6-12 months after evacuation is mandatory"],
    safetyNote: "Serial hCG monitoring after molar evacuation is essential - rising or plateauing hCG indicates persistent GTD requiring chemotherapy",
    distractorRationales: ["Twin pregnancy would show fetal poles, not a snowstorm pattern", "Complete hydatidiform mole is correct based on the snowstorm pattern and very high hCG", "Miscarriage would not show a snowstorm pattern or markedly elevated hCG", "Choriocarcinoma is a potential sequela of molar pregnancy but the primary diagnosis is the mole"],
    lessonLink: "/emergency/lessons/gestational-trophoblastic-disease"
