    correctAnswer: 1,
    rationaleLong: "This patient has eclampsia, defined as new-onset seizures in a patient with preeclampsia (hypertension + proteinuria in pregnancy). Eclampsia is a life-threatening obstetric emergency that can cause maternal death from cerebral hemorrhage, aspiration, and organ failure. The first-line medication for eclamptic seizures is IV magnesium sulfate, NOT benzodiazepines or phenytoin. Magnesium sulfate is the drug of choice for both treatment of eclamptic seizures and prevention of recurrent seizures (seizure prophylaxis in severe preeclampsia). The MAGPIE trial (10,000+ women) demonstrated that magnesium sulfate reduces the risk of eclampsia by 58% compared to placebo and is superior to phenytoin and benzodiazepines for this indication. Dosing protocol: (1) Loading dose: 4-6 grams IV over 15-20 minutes (given as a bolus), (2) Maintenance infusion: 1-2 grams/hour continuous IV infusion, (3) For recurrent seizures: additional 2-gram bolus IV. Magnesium sulfate therapeutic range: 4.8-8.4 mg/dL (2.0-3.5 mmol/L). Monitoring for magnesium toxicity is essential: (1) Deep tendon reflexes (DTRs) - first sign of toxicity is loss of DTRs (occurs at levels > 7-10 mg/dL), (2) Respiratory depression (occurs at levels > 12-15 mg/dL), (3) Cardiac arrest (occurs at levels > 25-30 mg/dL). The antidote for magnesium toxicity is IV calcium gluconate 1 gram (10 mL of 10% solution) given over 3-5 minutes. Blood pressure should be controlled concurrently with IV labetalol (20 mg bolus, double every 10 minutes up to 80 mg) or IV hydralazine (5-10 mg) to prevent cerebral hemorrhage from severe hypertension. The target is SBP < 160 mmHg and DBP < 110 mmHg. Definitive treatment for eclampsia is delivery of the baby and placenta.",
