    stem: "A 26-year-old female presents to the ED reporting she was sexually assaulted 6 hours ago. She is tearful and has visible bruising on her inner thighs. What is the emergency nurse's priority approach?",
    options: ["Immediately perform a complete forensic examination before any other care", "Provide compassionate trauma-informed care: assess for life-threatening injuries, offer emotional support, explain the examination process, and obtain informed consent before forensic evidence collection", "Ask detailed questions about the assault circumstances for the police report", "Administer emergency contraception and STI prophylaxis without examination"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    rationaleLong: "Caring for a sexual assault survivor requires a trauma-informed, patient-centered approach that prioritizes the patient's safety, emotional wellbeing, and autonomy. The emergency nurse's priority approach includes several key elements: (1) Ensure safety and privacy: provide a private room, minimize the number of staff present, and ensure the patient feels safe. (2) Assess for life-threatening injuries first: perform a primary assessment for injuries that require immediate medical treatment before forensic examination. (3) Provide emotional support: offer a calm, non-judgmental presence, believe the patient's account, avoid victim-blaming language, and offer access to a sexual assault nurse examiner (SANE) and/or victim advocate. (4) Explain the examination process thoroughly: before any examination, the patient must understand what will happen and why. Informed consent is MANDATORY for the forensic examination - the patient has the right to accept or decline any or all parts of the examination. (5) Collect forensic evidence with informed consent: the SAFE (Sexual Assault Forensic Examination) kit should be collected by a trained SANE nurse if available. Evidence collection is most effective within 72 hours but can be attempted up to 120 hours after the assault. Key aspects: do NOT ask the patient to change clothes or shower before evidence collection, collect clothing in paper (not plastic) bags, document all injuries with photographs (with consent), and collect swabs, fingernail scrapings, and other specimens per protocol. (6) Offer prophylactic medications: emergency contraception (levonorgestrel 1.5 mg PO if within 72 hours, or ulipristal acetate if within 120 hours), STI prophylaxis (ceftriaxone IM for gonorrhea, azithromycin PO for chlamydia, metronidazole PO for trichomoniasis), hepatitis B vaccination if unvaccinated, and HIV post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) if indicated. (7) Safety planning and follow-up referrals.",
