    rationaleLong: "This patient presents with classic placenta previa - painless, bright red vaginal bleeding in the third trimester. Placenta previa occurs when the placenta partially or completely covers the internal cervical os. The bleeding occurs when the lower uterine segment begins to thin and dilate in late pregnancy, disrupting the placental attachment and exposing maternal blood vessels. The absolute contraindication in placenta previa is digital vaginal examination. Inserting a finger into the vagina and through the cervix can disrupt the placenta covering the os, causing massive, life-threatening hemorrhage that may require emergent hysterectomy to control. Even a gentle digital exam can precipitate catastrophic bleeding from the disrupted placenta. The rule is: 'NO digital exam until placenta previa is excluded by ultrasound.' Transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound (which does NOT enter the cervical os) should be used to confirm placental location. Management of placenta previa with active bleeding depends on gestational age and bleeding severity: (1) Hemodynamically stable with term gestation (> 37 weeks): plan for cesarean delivery, (2) Hemodynamically stable preterm (< 37 weeks): admit for monitoring, tocolysis if contracting, corticosteroids for fetal lung maturity if < 34 weeks, blood type and crossmatch, (3) Hemodynamically unstable: emergent cesarean delivery regardless of gestational age. All patients with placenta previa require cesarean delivery because the placenta blocks the birth canal. The emergency nurse should establish 2 large-bore IVs, type and crossmatch at least 4 units PRBCs, apply continuous fetal monitoring, and monitor maternal hemodynamics closely. External fetal monitoring and pulse oximetry are appropriate and should be applied.",
