    correctAnswer: 1,
    rationaleLong: "This patient has multiple risk factors for venous thromboembolism (VTE) that compound to create a very high-risk situation: (1) Pregnancy and postpartum state: pregnancy is a hypercoagulable state with increased clotting factors (factors VII, VIII, X, XII, von Willebrand factor, and fibrinogen), decreased anticoagulant proteins (protein S), and impaired fibrinolysis. The thrombotic risk is 5-10 times higher during pregnancy and peaks in the postpartum period, remaining elevated for 6-12 weeks after delivery. (2) Cesarean delivery: surgical delivery adds the risk of tissue injury (which activates the coagulation cascade), venous stasis from anesthesia, and longer recovery time with reduced mobility. Cesarean delivery increases VTE risk 2-5 times compared to vaginal delivery. (3) Immobilization: being mostly bedridden since delivery further increases venous stasis (one of Virchow's triad). The combination of all three elements of Virchow's triad is present: (1) hypercoagulability (pregnancy + postpartum), (2) venous stasis (immobilization + anesthesia effects), and (3) endothelial injury (surgical incision). This makes the postpartum period after cesarean delivery one of the highest-risk situations for VTE in all of medicine. Pulmonary embolism is a leading cause of maternal mortality in developed countries, accounting for approximately 9% of pregnancy-related deaths. Treatment includes therapeutic anticoagulation with IV heparin (low-molecular-weight heparin or unfractionated heparin). Warfarin and direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) cross into breast milk, so LMWH is the preferred anticoagulant for breastfeeding mothers.",
    learningObjective: "Identify the combination of postpartum hypercoagulability, surgical delivery, and immobilization as cumulative VTE risk factors",
